Source: News briefs [edited]

[A] India from PTI 26 Apr 2003 19:07 IST
<http://www.ptinews.com/nextstory.asp?main=Indian&ID=973&rec=none>
With 3 more people testing positive for the SARS virus in the country, the
number of such cases has gone up to 7, health ministry officials said here
today. Of the 3 freshly confirmed cases, one is being treated in Kasturba
Hospital, Mumbai and the other two in Apollo Hospital, Kolkata and Naidu
Hospital, Pune, the officials added.
[B] Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia from NY Times / AP 26 Apr 2003 11:32 AM ET
<http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/health/AP-SARS-Virus.html>
Health ministers from across east Asia came up with a joint plan to fight
SARS during a meeting here Saturday [26 Apr 2003].
The Asian health ministers approved a plan to boost screening at
international departure points, bar travelers with SARS symptoms, and
require health declaration forms for visitors from affected countries. "We
must use every weapon at our disposal," the regional director of WHO,
Shigeru Omi, told the health ministers and senior officials from South East
Asia, China, Hong Kong, Japan, and South Korea.
Omi said Saturday's meeting and a summit next week of South East Asian
leaders in Thailand could "determine the future course" of how nations
tackle SARS. "The threat posed by SARS is unprecedented," Omi said. "The
virus has already demonstrated its explosive power to cause sudden
outbreaks in a large number of countries. Tourism has almost disappeared,
normal life has been seriously disrupted."
[C] Azerbiajan from Reuter's UK 26 Apr 2003 16:44:09 GMT
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L26476506.htm>
5 people in Azerbaijan, including one just returned from China, are
undergoing observation in hospital with suspected cases of SARS, a source
in the Health Ministry said.
"Those taken to hospital in Baku have symptoms similar to those of SARS,"
the source told Reuters in the capital of the ex-Soviet state on the
Caspian Sea. "They have been isolated in separate rooms and are undergoing
tests and examinations. Clinical diagnosis can be confirmed in 2 or 3
days." The source said one of the patients suspected of suffering from SARS
had been working in China and returned to Azerbaijan last week, travelling
through Turkey. But state television showed a hospital doctor telling the
young man's relatives that he was only suffering from a cold. No details of
other patients were available.
