[7]
Date: Fri, 25 Apr 2003 14:08:20 -0700 (PDT)
From: V Switzer <rgexxx@yahoo.com>

SARS in suspected cases & well people
-----------------------------------
With the possible SARS coronavirus detected by the Canadian National
Microbiology Laboratory in well people and in people only meeting the
"suspected case" definition, the most important immediate question to ask
is, have there been any "probable" cases who had direct contact only with
suspected case(s), or contact with well people who had been exposed? I
would also be interested in knowing which tests were used in the Canadian
study and which in Hong Kong, where 90 per cent of probable cases tested
positive. I did not see in the ProMED-mail reports whether these tests
involved acute and convalescent sera, polymerase chain reaction (PCR), or
other type of viral analysis.
--
V Switzer, MSN, ARNP, COHN-S EHPEC
Employee Health Practitioners, Educators, &, Consultants
Bellevue, WA, USA
[These are legitimate questions for which we do not have specific answers
as yet. The reports on the testing conducted in the various countries
include results of PCR testing and antibody tests, but we do not have the
specifics of the data in Canada. Our current understanding is that, in the
case of Canada and Singapore, the overwhelming majority of reported cases
can be linked back to contact with other probable cases. There are a few
cases in Canada for whom the location of transmission has not been
identified as yet. These limited data support the currently held impression
that close contact with known SARS cases continues to be the primary route
of transmission. When good reliable diagnostic tests are available to
confirm infection with the SARS related virus, we will be able to identify
what proportion of "suspected" cases are due to SARS, and what proportion
of SARS infected individuals have minimal or no clinical illness associated
with their infections. - Mod.MPP]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[As of 26 Apr 2003, the worldwide cumulative total is 4836 cases with 293
deaths, reported from 26 countries. In the 24 hours since the last update,
190 new cases and 19 deaths have been reported. 154 of the newly reported
cases are from China, 17 from Hong Kong, 8 from Taiwan, 3 from Singapore,
and 2 each from Canada, Mongolia, the Philippines, and the USA.
With respect to the news brief from India, other newswire reports mention
that one of these cases is related to the imported case, who was attending
a wedding in Pune. The newswire reports all stress that these are confirmed
cases based on laboratory testing. As the number of cases of SARS reported
from India to WHO continues to be "one", we are curious where this
information is coming from, as the newswires do mention health ministry
officials in their announcements. It should be noted that the last report
on SARS from India to WHO was on 21 Apr 2003, and these additional cases
have been reported by the press since that date.
We have stressed in prior postings the need to maintain consistent clinical
and epidemiological criteria for case reporting, pending more information
on the sensitivity and specificity of currently available laboratory tests.
It is unclear whether these additional cases mentioned in the newswires fit
the case definition or are based on "laboratory confirmation", as the
newswire suggests. Clarification of this issue is of concern, as
introduction of local transmission of SARS within densely populated India
would be of significant import with regard to the containment of SARS. -
Mod.MPP]
